    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-12-06T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-12-06T19:00:00-05:00" n="169"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d169">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">837.61351/4457: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Cuba</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Braden</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Habana</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-12-06T19:00:00-05:00"
                            >December 6, 1943—7 p.m.</date>[Received 11:47 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>806. The Prime Minister in a confidential personal letter to me dated December
                        3<note n="32" xml:id="d169fn32">Not printed.</note> states that he has
                    received information to the effect that the Mexican Government in conjunction
                    with the Pepsi Cola Company and other American interests is disposed to purchase
                    100,000 tons of Cuban refined sugar—40,000 for the Pepsi Cola Company and 60,000
                    for the Mexican Sugar Institute—and to furnish Cuba in return with all the gas
                    oil required for its agricultural diversification<note n="33" xml:id="d169fn33"
                        >For details of the diversification program, see <ref target="#pg_223">pp.
                            223</ref> ff.</note> and Public Works Program. The gas oil and sugar
                    would be transported in Mexican bottoms exclusively. The Prime Minister inquires
                    whether such a plan would conflict with any existing regulations of our
                    Government and dwells once more on the difficulties; experienced by Cuba due to
                    restricted gas oil supplies.</p>
                <p>I am informing the Prime Minister that this matter has been referred to
                    Washington, pointing out, however, that the plan seems, of doubtful
                    practicability as it would require our consent to the production in 1944 of an
                    additional 100,000 tons of sugar and the earmarking of 40,000 tons thereof for a
                    private concern; and as, in line with basic pool principles, any gas oil
                    imported from Mexico would <pb facs="0196" n="182" xml:id="pg_182"/> probably
                    have to be charged to Cuba’s over-all petroleum products quota.</p>
                <p>I would appreciate receiving at the earliest opportunity an expression of the
                    Department’s views in the matter in order that I may reply to the Prime
                    Minister.</p>
                <p>Not repeated to Mexico City.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Braden</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
